description:
## Severity
Minor
## Dimension
concurrency
## Location
src/state/store.rs:173-182
## Violation
The StateWriteGuard Drop impl unconditionally flushes pending events to subscribers, even on panic unwind:

```rust
impl Drop for StateWriteGuard<'_> {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        for event in self.pending.drain(..) {
            // send() fails when there are zero subscribers — that's
            // fine, the event just has no audience.
            let _ = self.events.send(event);
        }
    }
}
```

The module doc claims this as a feature:

```rust
//! The write-guard-on-drop pattern means a panic during mutation
//! still emits the event (`Drop` runs on unwind).
```

But the panic semantics are dangerous: a writer that records `MessageAppended` then panics BEFORE actually completing the message append still tells subscribers "a message was appended." Subscribers (analytics, transcript writer) then act on state that doesn't match the SessionState — the transcript writer reads `conversation.messages` and finds the message is not there, OR worse, finds a half-populated message. The lock is poisoned but subscribers won't know that until they next try to read.

Additionally, std::thread::panicking() can be checked inside Drop — if true, we know we're unwinding and should NOT broadcast events that promise post-condition observability.

## Mandated refactor
Gate the flush on std::thread::panicking():

```rust
impl Drop for StateWriteGuard<'_> {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        if std::thread::panicking() {
            // Don't broadcast — state may be inconsistent. Subscribers
            // will discover the lock is poisoned on their next read.
            return;
        }
        for event in self.pending.drain(..) {
            let _ = self.events.send(event);
        }
    }
}
```

Alternatively, require explicit guard.commit() to flush; Drop without commit logs a warn.

